Abortion is legal when a woman's health is at risk, but situations that represent a threat to physical or psychological health are unclear. The law does not make any provision for rape or incest.

Sexual harassment is a crime in Mauritania. However, prejudices about misconduct towards women continue to be widespread.

It is a serious criminal offence for a man to have sex outside marriage. This crime has a maximum sentence of two years’ imprisonment and a £50 ($70 US) fine. It is widely believed that women are obliged to submit to conjugal rights if requested by their husband, but reports of prosecution for this offence are rare. There are stories of prostitution, though police raid brothels only once a month on average. Local police have little regard for women who have sex outside marriage. The only sign of religion is on the road.

In women’s prisons, women are often charged with adultery and are given heavy sentences. Despite the above laws, women in Mauritania are still not equal to men. “The most offensive fact about Mauritanian women's lives is the way they have been dramatically affected by increase in poverty,” Awa Diawara. “Back in the 1960s we helped each other. Now, women do not even help a sister who came into our community.”
